<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-485-429  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 485 429.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Oct 1 1990 n486 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army drafts CSC, Boeing. (the US Army Reserve Component AutomationSystem contract won by Computer Sciences Corp. and Boeing ComputerServices Co.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Moore, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Army awards the first phase of its $1.3 billion ReserveComponent Automation System (RCAS) contract to Boeing ComputerServices Co and Computer Sciences Corp. The first phase of thethree-step, 12-year systems integration project is for developmentof prototypes; Boeing's one-year phase one contract is valued at$15.8 million, while Computer Sciences' is estimated to be worth$15.3 million.andP;  Mobilization and administrative functions for theArmy National Guard and Army Reserve will be automated under RCAS;Posix-based workstations, custom Ada mobilization andadministrative software and a telecommunications link betweenNational Guard and Army Reserve units and major Army commands willbe used in the system.andP;  The companies will develop and demonstrateRCAS concepts in the first year; one contractor will be selectedin late 1991 to install the system in about 4,700 sites.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Boeing Computer Services Co. (contracts)Computer Sciences Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    BA; CSC.andO;Topic:     Government ContractsComputer Systems IntegrationMilitaryOffice AutomationUnited States. ArmyUnited States. Army ReserveUnited States. National Guard.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>